column322:
The Lakshadweep Surf club in Kavaratti is a bright beautiful surfing club,it is filled with a good collection of surf boards,well maintained, friendly people, the club basically helps young people fulfil their potential.
Their goal is to help young people become stronger, more resilient and celebrate this one amazing life we all have. Using surfing and the ocean as the interactive tools, they help the local inhabitants and make them understand they can overcome any challenge.
The best waves on the archepelago can be found at these club shore's. People from all over the world come to check out these unpopulated hidden frothing tides only to ride the waves, string them together to find good adrenaline rush!

column346:
Kadmat Island, also known as Cardamom Island, is a coral island belonging to the Amindivi subgroup of islands of the Lakshadweep archipelago in India. Measuring 9.3 kilometres (5.8 mi) in length, the island has a lagoon with a width of 1.5 kilometres (0.93 mi) covering an area of 25 square kilometres (9.7 sq mi). The ecological feature of the island is of coral reef with seagrass, and marine turtles which nestle here. The Ministry of Environment and Forests (India) has notified the island as a marine protected area for ensuring conservation of the island's animal, plant, or other type of organism, and other resources.
The only inhabited village on the island is Kadmat, which had a population of 5,389 according to 2011 census. Fisheries is the main economic activity on the island with agriculture limited to 5% of the land area. Tourism is allowed even for non-Indians and the attractions are kayaking, snorkeling and leisure trips by a glass-bottomed boat for scuba diving.

column513:
Plains are very thickly populated as compared to hills because of:

1.Warm and adequate climatic conditions for proper vegetation and living.

2.Rivers carry silt and deposit it in the plains thus making the plain soil more fertile.

3.The plain lands have more comfortable spaces for human settlements

column346:
Bangaram:

Bangaram is a tiny teardrop shaped island, which lies very close to Agatti and Kavaratti. The tourist resort on this island provides an amazing opportunity for guests to unwind from the pressures and tensions of modern life. Two small islands of Thinnakara and Parali also lie close to Bangaram enclosed by the same lagoon. During the night, phosphorescent plankton washed ashore on the coral sands impart a bluish glow to the beach, which is totally enchanting. Guests to this resort can either avail of the boat transfer or helicopter transfer from Agatti. Being the only uninhabited island resort in Lakshadweep it has got its own charm. An ideal destination for discerning exclusive tourists, Bangaram has carved its presence in the international tourist map.

column346:
Yesterday we finished our Lakshadweep trip along with life time memories. Incredible India. Lovely place & lovely peoples. The place is so so beautiful, pure, neat and clean that I can't explain in the words. What a landscape, crystal clear water, untouched coral reefs. I visited Maldives also and can confirm that our Lakshadweep is no where less than Maldives (except luxurious amenities).

We visited with our 1.5 year old little baby and stayed in Agatti Beach Resort. I recommended the GoL hospitality and services. The local staff, Hidayath and his colleague's are very caring and sincere persons. We got a family like treatment there. Also, the local peoples are having a positive gesture with smiling faces.
Water sport activities like scuba diving, snorkeling,  glass bottam ride erc are world class.

One suggestion to GoL, please include some salads & fruits in the food menu, specially for vegetarian peoples.

Must visit place for a lifelong memories.  Highly recommended.
Note: Who are looking for only luxurious amenities, can not be satisfied there.
